benevolent’). As usual in Welsh, the stress in <i>Elisse</i> is on the penultimate syllable <i>-li-</i>, which shifts to initial <i>El-</i> when the name is shortened to <i>Elis</i>. It later became confused with <i>Ellis</i> in 1 above."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gwynnog Farfsych ap Lles was born about 0870, in Wales, his father, Lles Llawddeog, was 21 and his mother, Lles LLawddeog, was 17. He married Fynwyla ferch Iorwerth before 0890, in Montgomeryshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 870–":"umbes 0870–Surnud","0870–Male":"0870–Surnud","0874–Male":"0874–Surnud","0890–Male":"0890–Surnud","0875–Female":"0875–Surnud","0850–0929":"0850–0929","0890–0960":"0890–0960","0922–1038":"0922–1038","0855–Female":"0855–Surnud","Abt 890":"umbes 0890","before 0874":"enne 0874","before 890":"enne 0890","0929":"0929","0890":"0890","0875":"0875","about 870":"umbes 0870","1038":"1038","0874":"0874","0960":"0960","0850":"0850","0870":"0870","0855":"0855","about 0890":"umbes 0890","0922":"0922","Powys, Cymru":"Powys, Wales, United Kingdom","Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","Wales":"Wales","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales","Powys, Wales":"Powys, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 870–":"noin 0870–Kuollut","0870–Male":"0870–Kuollut","0874–Male":"0874–Kuollut","0890–Male":"0890–Kuollut","0875–Female":"0875–Kuollut","0850–0929":"0850–0929","0890–0960":"0890–0960","0922–1038":"0922–1038","0855–Female":"0855–Kuollut","Abt 890":"noin 0890","before 0874":"ennen vuotta 0874","before 890":"ennen vuotta 0890","0929":"0929","0890":"0890","0875":"0875","about 870":"noin 0870","1038":"1038","0874":"0874","0960":"0960","0850":"0850","0870":"0870","0855":"0855","about 0890":"noin 0890","0922":"0922","Powys, Cymru":"Powys, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Montgomery